last_replies.name: Anonymous
last_replies.com:
Salt in advance. Roast in the oven on low heat for many hours. The skin will slowly dry out and the meat will become tender. Then finish it very briefly in a very hot oven or under a broiler so the skin goes from dry and tough to crisp and brittle.

You need a fairly big piece of meat for this. If it's too small, the meat may also dry out too much. For a small piece it's best to sous vide it and then finish by deep-frying. This gives acceptably crispy texture but in my experience it's slightly inferior to the traditional method which is even crispier. The benefit with sous vide is that it's possible to do the first cook well in advance, store in the fridge and then just finish in oil whenever you need it.
